Graduation project E-commerce¶

Goal: To analyze the product range, have a look at revenue generated by different goods in stock and make conclusions that would be useful for the marketing team.

Link to Tableau dashboard:¶

https://public.tableau.com/views/YandexGraduationProjectE-Commerce/Dashboard1?:language=en&:display_count=y&publish=yes&:origin=viz_share_link

Link to presentation PDF:¶

https://drive.google.com/file/d/10hg0H8hfEHc3h_kt4SBMFb9d5VWtdylz/view?usp=sharing

Table of contents¶

Step 1. General Information and preprocessing
Step 2. Exploratory data analysis

  • Unit prices
  • Unit quantities
  • Retail and individual customers division
  • Revenue from retail and individual customers
  • Low orders number and multiple orders number between users
  • Top 10 items for retail and individual users
  • Most common item pairs
  • Revenue from our top 50 users
  • Daily and monthly revenue
  • ARPPU
  • Retention
  • Cohort analysis
  • Top 10 selling products analysis
  • Season-dependance analysis
  • Names/keywords analysis

Step 3. Hypotheses testing

  • Do the retail users generate more revenue?
  • Does more orders means more revenue?

Step 4. Overall conclusion

Conclusion¶

The data contains more than 500000 rows with information about orders, items and their names, quantiy bought, prices per unit, transaction dates and user ids. The outliers were removed and some missing values were filled. The data represents a full year. The item prices are in range of 0-18. The user_id column still contains missing values that were filled with 0.

ret['seniority'] = round(((ret['day'] - ret['first_visit']).dt.days) / 30, 0)#.astype('timedelta64[M]')#.astype('int')

3. Hypotheses testing¶

1. Retail users generate more revenue?¶

$H_{0}$ - There is no statistically significant difference between the means of revenue in multiple-item orders and low-item orders.
$H_{a}$ - There is statistically significant difference between the means.
Significance level $\alpha$ = 0.5

In [142]:
print('Independent users revenue mean:', ind_rev.revenue.mean(), 'Retail users revenue mean:', ret_rev.revenue.mean())

Independent users revenue mean: 67.78702564102572 Retail users revenue mean: 305.39102854384134
In [143]:
alpha = .05

results = st.mannwhitneyu(rev_high_u.values, rev_low_u.values)

print('p-value: ', results.pvalue)

if (results.pvalue < alpha):
        print("We reject the null hypothesis")
else:
        print("We can't reject the null hypothesis")

p-value:  0.0
We reject the null hypothesis

Conclusion¶

We reject the null hypothesis - there's a difference between multiple-item orders and low-item orders. Multiple-item orders bring more revenue.

2. More orders means more revenue?¶

$H_{0}$ - There is no statistically significant difference between the means of revenue in low-orders and multi-orders customers.
$H_{a}$ - There is statistically significant difference between the means.
Significance level $\alpha$ = 0.5

We reject the null hypothesis

Conclusion¶

We reject the null hypothesis that the average revenue for the users who make more than 5 orders is the same as for the users that make more than 5 orders - there's a difference between them. The latter users have greater average revenue.

4. Overall conclusion¶

The unit prices of our products range between 0 to 17.88. The most common price is 1.25. Our users most often buy 1 item in terms of quantity, but there's a lot of orders with 2 and 12 of the same items. The number of unique items per order varies between 1 to 1078, but 75% is up to 28 (let's round to 30) items per order. If we divide our customers on those who order more than 30 (retail users) and less than 30 (individual users) and analyze their behavior separately, we'll find that only a small part of our user are individuals. These two categories of users also have differencies in top 10 items they buy. There's much more users that've made up to 4 orders this year - 75%. But turns out that users with more than 5 orders have bigger average revenue. There are products that we find in the same cart more often. Since most of orders are from retailers, these items are similar - same products with different color or design. The average paycheck from our top 50 users look very similar to all others - looks like they make mosk of the orders to refiil thir stocks. The average daily revenue is ~20500. The total revenue per month varies between 330000 (Feb, Apr) and 950000 (Nov). Average revenue per paying user ranging between 400 and 650. General retention each month is around 25-45%. There are some cohorts with greater retention (2018-12), and lesser (2019-05), we see general decline in retention during summer months and rise towards October-November. The Dec, 2018 cohort is the most profitable. Maybe because they hit two end-of-the-year holiday seasons, when sales are high. The Dec, 2019 cohort is a record holder for the first month profit. Also the August cohort speeded up towards the end of the year, hitting 17 cumulative revenue in 5 month - more everyone, except for Dec, 2018 cohort. Top 10 best sellers bring up to 50 revenue per day, but often exceed that number. The monthly total revenue for these items depends on month, but usually around 2000-4000. The top 10 most ordered items are ordered more than 750 times per month. Most impressive season-related rise in orders is expectedly November. Season-related declines usually happens in June or April. Some of the products are sets and average quantity per order for them is high, thus it might be better for our customers if we start to sell them in bigger sets. In terms of materials wooden and paper items bring more revenue than glass/metal/ceramic. There are some keyweords in product names that bring more revenue - such as ART, EAR, BAG in total; ORNAMENT, CARS, SPICE in average revenue.
